      "raw_response": "{\n  \"final_bugs\": [\n    {\n      \"description\": \"The algorithm enumerates all pairs of problems within each topic, leading to O(\u2211 cnt_a^2) time, which can be O(n^2) for inputs where many problems share the same topic (e.g., all n problems have the same topic). This will cause a Time Limit Exceeded on large test cases.\",\n      \"triggering_input\": \"1\\n200000\\n\" + \"\\n\".join(\"1 \" + str(i) for i in range(1,200001)),\n      \"fix\": \"Replace the pair enumeration with a combinatorial formula. Compute the number of bad triples as:\\n\\nbad = \u03a3_a C(cnt_a, 2) * (n - cnt_a) + \u03a3_b C(cnt_b, 2) * (n - cnt_b) - \u03a3_i (cnt_a[a_i] - 1) * (cnt_b[b_i] - 1)\\n\\nThen answer = total - bad. This runs in O(n) time and fits the constraints.\",\n      \"confirmed\": true,\n      \"reasoning\": \"The current double loop over each topic's problem list is quadratic in the size of the topic group. For a topic with 200,000 problems it would iterate ~2e10 pairs, which is infeasible. The combinatorial formula computes the same count in linear time and matches the problem's constraints.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}",
